subsection.p:
We will first see that the eigenvalues of a square matrix appear as the roots of a particular polynomial. To begin, notice that we originally defined an eigenvector as a nonzero vector \vvec that satisfies the equation A\vvec = \lambda\vvec. We will rewrite this as
\begin{aligned} A\vvec \amp {}={} \lambda\vvec \\ A\vvec - \lambda\vvec \amp {}={} \zerovec \\ A\vvec - \lambda I\vvec \amp {}={} \zerovec \\ (A-\lambda I)\vvec \amp {}={} \zerovec\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
In other words, an eigenvector \vvec is a solution of the homogeneous equation (A-\lambda I)\vvec=\zerovec. This puts us in the familiar territory explored in the next activity.

example.p:
If we write the characteristic equation for the matrix A = \left[\begin{array}{rr} -4 \amp 4 \\ -12 \amp 10 \\ \end{array}\right] , we see that
\begin{aligned} \det(A-\lambda I) \amp {}={} 0 \\ \\ \det \left[\begin{array}{rr} -4 - \lambda \amp 4 \\ -12 \amp 10 - \lambda \\ \end{array}\right] \amp {}={} 0 \\ \\ (-4-\lambda)(10-\lambda) + 48 \amp {}={} 0 \\ \lambda^2-6\lambda + 8 {}={} 0 \\ (\lambda-4)(\lambda-2) {}={} 0\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
This shows us that the eigenvalues are \lambda = 4 and \lambda=2.

To find the eigenvalues of a triangular matrix, we remember that the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of the entries on the diagonal. For instance, the following triangular matrix has the characteristic equation
\begin{aligned} \det\left( \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ \end{array}\right] -\lambda I\right) \amp {}={} \det \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 4-\lambda \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -2-\lambda \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 3-\lambda \\ \end{array}\right] \\ \\ \amp {}={}(4-\lambda)(-2-\lambda)(3-\lambda) = 0\text{,} \end{aligned}
showing that the eigenvalues are the diagonal entries \lambda = 4,-2,3.

li.p:
We have
A - 3I = \mattwo{-2}{2}{2}{-2} \sim \mattwo{1}{-1}{0}{0}\text{.}
The null space \nul(A-3I) is one-dimensional with basis \twovec{1}{1}.

We have
A - (-1)I = \mattwo{2}{2}{2}{2} \sim \mattwo{1}{1}{0}{0}\text{.}
The null space \nul(A+I) is one-dimensional with basis \twovec{-1}{1}.

There are three eigenvalues, \lambda=2 has multiplicity 3, \lambda=-3 has multiplicity 10, and \lambda=5 has multiplicity 1. We know that
\begin{aligned} 1 \leq \dim E_2 \amp {}\leq{} 3 \\ 1 \leq \dim E_{-3} \amp {}\leq{} 10 \\ 1 \leq \dim E_5 \amp {}\leq{} 1\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
We can guarantee that \dim E_{5} = 1, but we can say nothing further about the other two eigenspaces.
